entry.title: [//media] Pass dest GL capabilities to UploadVideoFrameToGLTexture()
entry.content:
UploadVideoFrameToGLTexture() will need to query the capabilities of

`destination_gl` to know whether YUV-RGB conversion is supported. This

CL passes those capabilities through from callsites in preparation.



NOTE: I originally wanted to just pass in gpu::ContextProvider rather

than passing in `destination_gl` and get both the GLContext and the

Capabilities from it. However, that's complicated by the Blink use

case: it hides its underlying ContextProvider under multiple layers

and exposes it only as a RasterContextProvider (it is a

viz::ContextProviderCommandBuffer under the hood). Rather than make

changes there, I just passed through the Capabilities directly.

entry.title: [//gpu] Cache GpuMemoryBuffers that ScopedMapping uses
entry.content:
ScopedMapping currently creates a GpuMemoryBuffer from the passed-in

cached GpuMemoryBufferHandle, destroying the GpuMemoryBuffer when it is

destroyed. We are seeing that this behavior can cause performance

regressions when porting clients from direct usage of GpuMemoryBuffer

itself - when clients hold onto a long-lived GpuMemoryBuffer and

Map()/Unmap() from it, some GpuMemoryBuffer implementations implement

internal optimizations to limit overhead between Unmap() and subsequent

Map() operations.



This CL changes ScopedMapping to take in a GpuMemoryBuffer* rather than

a Handle. Creators of ScopedMapping now create and cache a

GpuMemoryBuffer for the relevant Mailbox rather than just the

GpuMemoryBufferHandle.



ScopedMapping still Maps()/Unmaps() the buffer at creation/destruction,

i.e., the functional behavior from the client POV is unchanged.



Bug: 1431314, 1430974

`pass_response_pipe_to_client` argument which is set only for

downloading the response as a blob using sync XHR. This CL also renames

it to `download_to_blob` argument.

entry.title: [Glanceables] Add post login glanceables metrics recorder
entry.content:
Add metrics which record a histogram at each time we would want to

fetch data shown in post login glanceables. QPS can be estimated by

recording each place that data is currently fetched, and at places we

would want to trigger a fetch.



There are three places this metric is recorded at:

- Calendar event fetch

- Overview mode starting

- Full restore notification show



The metric is split by different delay amounts, being 0/15/30 seconds.

This is used to help see the effects of how queries would be throttled

when the metric is not recorded within the same 0/15/30 second interval.

entry.title: Extensions: WFH: Lacros feature parity with Ash
entry.content:
Features now (or previously) available in Lacros:

* Open a file with an extension when launch type is "single-client".

* Open files with an extension when launch type is "multiple-clients".

* Allowlisted extensions bypass the permission dialog.

* WFH supported QO extensions no longer use "apps".

* .grdp expanded to include Lacros.

* Deduplicated GetBaseNamesForIntent() for Lacros usage.

* Created new _util files to avoid duplication.

* SupportsWebFileHandlers() allowlist bypass now available for Lacros.

* Permission dialog now available in Lacros.

* Refactored unwieldy if else statement nesting in lacros controller.

* Lacros now prefers to reuse an existing window when opening a tab.

* Made some comments clearer.

* Refactored multiclient logic for clarity and possible reuse later.

* Lacros is now able to see multiple clients in the list.

* Allowlisted extensions can bypass the permission dialog.

entry.title: pip-tilt: Add tilt effect to CrOS PiP
entry.content:
The commit introduces the ability to tilt the Picture-in-Picture (PiP)

window through the pinch gseture. During the pinch gesture, the window’s

angle is changed with `transform` following the angle of the pinch

gesture.



To achieve this new effect, two changes were made:



1 . A new `angle` value was added to `GestureEventDetails`. `angle` is

defined as the angle between the horizontal axis and the line

connecting each individual finger location to the focal point, and they

are stored so that their `ActionIndex` matches vector's index. Like

`scale`, this value is calculated by `ScaleGestureDetector` and set by

`GestureProvider` during pinch gestures.



2. `PipWindowResizer::Pinch` now takes `angle` as parameter and passes

it to `PipWindowResizer::CalculateTransformForPinch` which calculates

and applies the appropriate `Rotate` to transform. In addition, since

the `Rotate`'s anchor point is the origin (top-left),

`PipWindowResizer::CalculateBoundsForPinch` edits the bounds so that

the rotation is centered in the window.



Demo video:

(https://drive.google.com/file/d/1pm3BwCY2ew1b_TgveiM41pYR3KHN3zNP)

entry.title: Use FormData in TTFCC DryRun to check focusability of a field.
entry.content:
TouchToFillDelegateAndroidImpl::DryRun is invoked twice, as explained

below: AutofillManager receives an event on a field and invokes

AskForValuesToFill. Flow goes to OnBeforeAskForValuesToFill implemented

by an Observer, here keyboard_suppressor. KeyboardSuppressor invokes

TouchToFillDelegateAndroidImpl::IntendsToShowTouchToFill that triggers

pre-parsing DryRun on the form field. Followed by ParseAsync ->

OnAskForValuesToFillImpl, that invokes

TouchToFillDelegateAndroidImpl::TryToShowTouchToFill that trigger

TouchToFillDelegateAndroidImpl::DryRun for the second time on the

form field.



DryRun uses FormStructure to get the AutofillField and check it’s

focusability. By using FormStructure, DryRun doesn’t always have the

up-to-date information about the field. The solution here is to use FormData

that has up-to-date information about focusability and visibility changes in a

field. This is done to avoid DryRun failures due to outdated field information

resulting in unexpected behaviour where TTFCC bottomsheet shows up after

keyboard accessory



Demo: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1LcBrxPLfwkDu151TohG9JKYH6-IyaPke/view?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-2o_BS4YAdsOcx6phBV985w

entry.title: partitions: Add buffer partition escape-hatch
entry.content:
Per https://crbug.com/1444624#c44, we have discovered a quarantine leak

in the Buffer partition causing unacceptable memory overhead when

MiraclePtr is brought live in the renderer process.



We think we've found the leak (https://crbug.com/1444624#c45), but out

of an abundance of caution, we add an escape-hatch to turn off BRP in

the buffer partition. We do not want to use it, but it will be necessary

if we cannot wrestle quarantine bloat under control at 99P (especially

on Android).
